I would argue that accepted wisdom believes that code continues to work  
as specified which is not necessarily as intended.

Unit tests only let you know that your system works as you have  
specified it to.  You will not be able to specific everything (your  
first attempts try to specify only what you think could break) and not  
everything you have specified will be done so correctly (bugs in yours  
tests).  Using other techniques like code coverage will help - as well  
as the prescribed test-driven approach of making things fail before  
they pass.  If I am changing working (i.e. the associated tests pass)  
code - then I usually re-introduce the red bar prior to getting the  
green bar.  No (at least almost no) line of code in the application is  
added unless it&#39;s role is to make a test pass.

